stylometry: We simulated demand for Adam's Landscaping (a landscaping company that Matt works for). We simulated demand and looked at profit of each type of job that they did: concrete, hardscape, installation and maintenance. We used this simulated demand to try to figure out if the demand was such that we needed to hire more workers, or if the amount of workers they have now is good enough. We used @RISK to simulate our demand for each job and looked at each job at first on a case by case basis and then finally all together. We learned that they could potentially elliminate concrete from their services because they actually lose money on concrete, and that they do not need to hire any more workers, that the workers they have now are enough to take care of the demand necessary without incurring other costs such as buying or renting more equipment. I also personally learned how to apply a simulation model to the real world and create my own template and model.
